## ADR (Architecture Decision Records)

### When to Create ADRs
Create an ADR for any non-trivial architectural decision:

- Choosing between major technology options
- Significant API design changes
- Performance vs maintainability trade-offs
- Security implementation decisions
- Breaking changes to existing patterns

### ADR Structure
```markdown
# ADR-001: Decision Title

## Status
Accepted | Proposed | Rejected

## Context
What problem are we solving? What constraints exist?

## Decision
What did we decide and why?

## Consequences
What becomes easier/harder? What are the trade-offs?

## Alternatives Considered
What other options did we evaluate?

- **Option A**: Pros/cons
- **Option B**: Pros/cons

## Implementation
How will this be implemented? Timeline? Migration plan?
```

### ADR Organization
```
docs/
  adr/
    001-use-typescript-strict-mode.md
    002-adopt-nx-monorepo.md
    003-implement-error-boundaries.md
```

## API Documentation

### OpenAPI/Swagger Standards
For HTTP APIs, maintain OpenAPI specifications:

```yaml
openapi: 3.0.3
info:
  title: User Management API
  version: 1.0.0
  description: User account and profile management
paths:
  /users:
    post:
      summary: Create new user
      requestBody:
        required: true
        content:
          application/json:
            schema:
              $ref: '#/components/schemas/UserInput'
      responses:
        '201':
          description: User created successfully
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                $ref: '#/components/schemas/User'
components:
  schemas:
    UserInput:
      type: object
      required:
        - email
        - name
      properties:
        email:
          type: string
          format: email
        name:
          type: string
```

## Auto-Generated Documentation

### CI Documentation Generation
Configure CI to automatically generate and publish documentation:

```yaml
# .github/workflows/docs.yml
name: Generate Docs
on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:

jobs:
  docs:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3
      - uses: actions/setup-node@v3
        with:
          node-version: 18
          cache: 'pnpm'
      - run: pnpm install
      - run: pnpm docs:generate
      - run: pnpm docs:publish
```

### TypeDoc Configuration
```javascript
// typedoc.config.js
module.exports = {
  entryPoints: ['./src/index.ts'],
  out: './docs/api',
  exclude: ['**/*.spec.ts', '**/*.test.ts'],
  includeVersion: true,
  disableSources: false,
  excludePrivate: true,
  excludeProtected: true,
  hideGenerator: true,
  theme: 'default',
  readme: './README.md',
  name: 'My Library',
  tsconfig: './tsconfig.json'
};
```

## Code Comments Standards

### When to Comment
- **Complex business logic** - Explain why, not what
- **Workarounds** - Document temporary solutions and TODOs
- **Public APIs** - JSDoc as specified above
- **Configuration choices** - Why specific values were chosen

### Comment Style
```typescript
// ❌ Bad: states the obvious
const total = price * quantity; // multiply price by quantity

// ✅ Good: explains business logic
const total = price * quantity; // Apply volume discount threshold check

// ✅ Good: documents workaround
// TODO: Remove when API supports bulk operations
// Using individual requests due to rate limiting
for (const item of items) {
  await api.update(item);
}
```

